<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Oil helps industrial output return to pre-recession levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp increase in oil and gas extraction in November helped bring overall
industrial production back to pre-recession levels, while official figures
published yesterday also pointed to a quickening of manufacturing output.
The Central Statistical Office yesterday reported a 0.4 per cent increase in
seasonally adjusted output in the production industries in November to show
a 3.9 per cent rise on November 1992.
Manufacturing output increased by 0.3 per cent in November and was 2.5 per
cent higher than in November 1992.
Taking three months' figures, considered by the CSO to be a more reliable
guide, overall industrial production increased by 1.2 per cent in September,
October and November compared with the previous three months and was 2.7 per
cent up on the three months to the end of November 1992. Manufacturing
production rose 0.8 per cent in the latest three months compared with the
June-to-August period and was 1.8 per cent higher than in the three months
to November 1992.
The coming on stream of new oil and gas fields as well as cold autumn
weather, which boosted demand for gas and electricity, lifted the production
industries output index to 100.2 in November.
This was its highest level since July 1990, on the eve of the recession, and
slightly higher than the average for 1990 that now serves as the index base.
Manufacturing accounts for nearly 85 per cent of the production industries'
output, which also includes mining, quarrying, oil and gas extraction and
electricity, gas and water supply.
Oil and gas extraction in November was 24 per cent higher than in November
1992. It jumped by 5.8 per cent between October and November, to come close
to its previous record output of May 1987. Oil and gas extraction in the
three months to November was up 2.6 per cent on the previous three months
and 15.8 per cent up on the three months to November 1992.
Output of the electricity, gas and water supply industries was 4.5 per cent
higher in the three months to November compared with the previous three
months and 4.7 per cent up on the same period of 1992. CSO statisticians
said that some 3 percentage points of the growth in electricity and gas
supplied in the latest period reflected the effects of unusually cold
weather in October and November.
Manufacturing output between October and November was boosted by a jump in
chemical production and a rise in tobacco output ahead of the November 30
Budget.
The latest three-month figures pointed to strong output growth in the oil
refining, computer and electronic components industries and in the
production of building materials and vehicles. However, output declined in
older industries such as shipbuilding and mechanical engineering.
CSO statisticians warned that the latest 0.8 per cent three months on three
months increase in manufacturing output could give too favourable a picture
of UK production trends. The late spring bank holiday depressed output in
the three months to the end of August.
Nonetheless, they estimated that manufacturing output was growing at an
underlying annual trend rate of 1.5 per cent in November against 1 per cent
in the previous month while the trend growth rate for the production
industries as a whole was 2.5 per cent.
Other figures released by CSO and the Department of Employment yesterday
revealed a slight upturn in manufacturing productivity growth to 3.6 per
cent in the 12 months to November from 3.3 per cent in the year to October.
However, the year-on-year growth of manufacturing output per head slowed to
3.8 per cent in the three months ended November from 5.3 per cent in the
three months to the end of August.
Unit wage costs in manufacturing rose in the three months ended November,
the first such rise last year.
</TEXT>
