<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / George calls for a cut in recriminations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, put it last night,
improving the financing of Britain's 2.5m small companies is 'an amorphous
sort of problem'.
The Bank's paper, following its inquiry among banks and small business
groups last year, does not propose any simple solution. Instead it argues
that the two sides have more in common than is generally thought, and should
work to improve understanding further.
Mr George last night rebutted the notion that banks are to blame for the
55,000 failures among small businesses each year. He argued that a more
stable economy 'would go a very long way to reducing the tensions that have
grown up'.
He had been encouraged by the amount of agreement in spite of the
'exaggerated expectations' of some small businesses and 'insensitivity' of
some banks. The debate should be 'carried forward in a constructive way,
with rather less mutual recrimination'.
The conclusion that the two sides should talk to each other more is
uncontroversial. But Mr George seems to have decided that someone should say
it.
The exercise can be seen as part of Mr George's effort to establish
independence from the Treasury. By setting its own terms, the Bank has
distanced itself from inquiries into loan margins ordered in 1991 and 1993
by Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor.
The Bank reaches seven conclusions, which it says are its own rather than
agreed principles. But it nevertheless tried to ensure that they were backed
by banks and small companies. It held a meeting of all sides last month to
discuss a final draft.
The paper's conclusions are:
Banks are committed to the finance of small business, and are trying to
provide alternatives to lending through overdrafts. Other forms of financing
include medium-term and long-term loans at fixed and floating interest
rates. Bank managers will have to be better trained to assess the right mix
of finance.
Most small companies accept the need to improve financial and management
skills. According to one estimate, just 10 per cent of very small businesses
produce adequate accounts. Some banks may consider offering better terms to
small businesses with well-trained managers.
Late payment of bills remains a significant problem for many small
businesses and may lead to them collapsing. A change of business culture is
needed, and both banks and small companies increasingly support a statutory
right to interest on unpaid bills. The government is consulting on this now.
There should be measures to encourage equity investment in small companies.
Banks may find this costly because of the management expertise required, but
venture capital companies and 'business angels' should be encouraged. A
replacement for the Unlisted Securities Market could be 'valuable'.
There are worries about the impact on small businesses of new legislation
such as the Consumer Credit Act and changes in the insolvency rules. Banks
have argued that if their claim to assets in insolvencies is weakened, this
will make them less likely to lend to small businesses.
Small companies have particular difficulties entering new export markets.
This may be helped by selling unpaid debt at a discount through methods
including factoring and invoice discounting.
All parties involved in the discussions accept that banks are not public
utilities, and need to 'price risk realistically'. The risks and costs
associated with small business lending are relatively high.
One difficulty with these principles is that they are not worded precisely
enough to form targets. Although the British Bankers' Association emphasised
yesterday that the proportion of fixed-term lending was rising, its leaders
said this figure could not be used to measure future progress.
This means that the problem may not only be amorphous, but have an
intangible solution. Mr George appears to think that the initiative will be
judged by whether public acrimony between banks and small businesses has
eased when he re-examines the problem later this year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
