<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Exports up as regions report improved trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Export orders for east Midlands companies have started to rise again after
declining during the summer, the Association of East Midlands Chambers of
Commerce said yesterday.
The survey was published as the latest report on business performance in
north-east England and Cumbria recorded, for the fourth quarter of 1993, the
highest ever positive balances for home sales, home orders and profits since
the survey began in mid-1990, before the recession hit the area.
In the latest survey of business performance at 353 companies in the east
Midlands, the chambers found 36 per cent of companies reporting an increase
in export orders in December, compared with 27 per cent in September and 38
per cent in June.
But the level of domestic business appears to have flattened out after a
surge of orders last spring. The chambers said 40 per cent of companies had
bigger order books in December than three months before, compared with 42
per cent in September and June and 28 per cent last March.
The east Midlands data illustrate the uneven spread of recovery. Last week,
the west Midlands chambers reported a fall in the number of service
companies increasing export orders, and a small rise in manufacturers with
higher export orders.
However, both regions have large amounts of unused capacity. The east
Midlands chambers reported that 32 per cent of companies were operating at
full capacity, 4 percentage points higher than September but 8 percentage
points lower than June.
Last month, 59 per cent of companies were expecting a rise in turnover, but
only 45 per cent expected a rise in profitability. The main concern of
companies remained a cut in interest rates, the east Midlands chambers said.
Meanwhile, Business Survey North, the quarterly report by the Northern
Development Company, the region's economic regeneration body, said most
companies in north east England and Cumbria appeared to have put recession
behind them. The report was produced in association with the Teesside and
Tyne and Wear Chambers of Commerce.
Following two successive quarterly falls, export sales and orders were up,
plant and machinery investment reached a new peak and training expenditure
rose sharply, in response to continuing skills shortages.
The survey is based on responses from 744 companies, 40 per cent of them
manufacturers. Of the respondents, 21.7 per cent were running at over 90 per
cent capacity, compared with 27.5 per cent in the previous quarter.
</TEXT>
