<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / OFT to probe sales of electrical warranties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, has asked the Office of Fair
Trading to investigate the sale of extended warranties on electrical goods,
following allegations that consumers were being 'ripped off' by retailers.
In a written question last week, Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer
spokesman, claimed electrical stores were selling extended warranties for up
to three times more than manufacturers charged for their own schemes.
Retailers were failing to tell customers that cheaper extended warranties -
which provide additional protection after the expiry of standard product
guarantees - were often available directly from manufacturers.
The OFT confirmed yesterday that the matter had been referred to it by Mr
Hamilton, and it was conducting inquiries with a view to launching an
investigation.
Such an investigation would have important implications for electrical
retailers, and particularly Dixons, the UK's largest, where extended
warranty business is thought to account for up to 10 per cent of sales and
gross profits.
Mr Griffiths said electrical stores were using the sale of warranties to
inflate profits during the recession.
'What is at issue is the failure to spell out to purchasers any alternative
to the stores' own warranty schemes,' he said. 'Stores must not be allowed
to profiteer at the expense of consumers.'
Among examples cited by Mr Griffiths were a branch of Currys, part of the
Dixons group, selling a five-year warranty for a Sony hi-fi system for
Pounds 155, when Sony could provide its own warranty for Pounds 60, and a
branch of Comet, part of the Kingfisher group, charging Pounds 119 for a
five-year warranty for a Sony system, compared with the manufacturer's
Pounds 60.
Mr John Clare, Dixons' chief executive, said retailers' warranties were more
expensive 'because they are different'. Manufacturers' warranties often
covered only the failure of parts - sometimes with important exclusions -
while those offered by retailers included all parts and labour, as well as
accidental damage.
He said: 'Retailers can give better service than manufacturers. We would
often exchange a product with a new one if it was not repairable, or even
replace it with another manufacturer's product.'
Mr Clare added that manufacturers' schemes were sometimes priced
unrealistically.
Kingfisher criticised the proportion of Dixons' profits from extended
warranties during its failed takeover bid in 1990. Dixons no longer
publishes separate results for its financial services division, which
includes extended warranties, but the business is thought to make a gross
profit of about Pounds 30m a year.
One retailing analyst said: 'Extended warranties are part of the cut and
thrust of negotiating over pricing.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
