<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Truro bus staff to hold third strike vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The RMT transport union is holding a third postal strike ballot of its 500
members who work for the Western National bus company after facing a court
injunction threatening sequestration of funds and fining of union officials.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, the union's general secretary, has called off a planned
one-day strike tomorrow at the Truro-based company after consulting union
members there.
A High Court judge granted the company an injunction last week after a
second ballot produced only a 188-185 vote in favour of a strike. Western
National said 12 employees had either not received ballot papers or had
received them but not had enough time to return them.
The union said there had been a problem caused by changes of address and the
slowness of postal deliveries over Christmas. The ballot was conducted by
the independent Electoral Ballot Services.
The union had called the second ballot after the first ballot produced a
176-164 vote for a strike. A number of members had failed to receive voting
papers in the first ballot, the union said.
Aslef, the train drivers' union, yesterday decided to call a strike ballot
of its 2,000 members at London Transport after the breakdown of talks on the
introduction of a five-day working week.
</TEXT>
