<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / 'Corrupt' reform of councils attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Charges of 'gerrymandering' in the reform of local government structure in
Scotland were brushed aside by Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, in the
Commons last night.
Labour and Liberal Democrat MPs insisted that proposals to replace the
existing 53 district councils, nine regional councils and three island
councils with 28 single-tier authorities were designed to improve the
electoral prospects of the Conservative party.
Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, denounced the Local
Government (Scotland) bill as 'shabby, politically corrupt and
anti-democratic'. He said that it would 'increase the dead weight of
bureaucracy'.
The 'politically corrupt, wasteful legislation' would be rejected by voters
in the local elections this May, he said.
Mr Jim Wallace, Liberal Democrat spokesman, said his party was in favour of
single-tier authorities but was not prepared to support a bill that was
'motivated by purely party-political reasons'.
Mr Lang said MPs and peers would have opportunities to suggest changes to
the local authority boundaries proposed by the government during the later
stages of the bill's passage through parliament. He accused the Convention
of Scottish Local Authorities of burying its head in the sand by opposing
the bill.
The bill was given a second reading by a government majority of 41
(318-277).
</TEXT>
