<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / DTI shake-up scraps post of chief scientist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry is to abolish the post of chief
scientist as part of a reorganisation of top jobs aimed at improving the
department's work to assist industrial competitiveness.
The announcement was greeted with 'disappointment' by Ms Fiona Steele, head
of technology policy at the Confederation of British Industry, who said the
abolition of the science adviser's job 'diminishes the role of science and
technology right across the government'.
Dr John Mulvey, secretary of the Save British Science campaign, said it
would be 'a serious step backwards' while Dr Lewis Moonie, Labour science
spokesman, called the change 'sadly predictable'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said the changes marked
'another step in restructuring the department to ensure that it is best
placed to fulfil my principal objective of helping UK business to win in
world markets'.
Under the reorganisation, taking place on March 1, scientific issues will be
dealt with by officials examining broad industrial problems in a revamped
'industrial sponsorship' division. Science and technology currently have
their own separate unit.
The department will not seek a replacement for Mr Geoffrey Robinson, chief
science and technology adviser, who leaves next month after less than two
years.
The department denied that the move devalued the role of science and
technology. 'We are incorporating this area most closely within the rest of
the organisation,' it said.
In recent years the DTI has reduced funding for research and development,
arguing that this is a job for the private sector, and has focused on
promoting good management practice and transfer of existing technologies to
companies.
Mr Alastair Macdonald, a deputy secretary currently in charge of one of the
DTI's industry divisions, will supervise all the department's work in
'sponsoring' specific business sectors.
The department's work on technology transfer and the spreading of management
best-practice will be linked with efforts to assist small and medium-size
enterprises.
</TEXT>
