<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Insider dealers fined Pounds 1,500
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two chartered accountants were each fined Pounds 1,500 at Inner London crown
court yesterday after being convicted of insider dealing by using
confidential knowledge of a planned hostile takeover bid.
Mr Ian Morrisey, who works for Hope, Agar and Staines, and Ms Lorelie
Staines, formerly with accountants Kidsons Impey, both persuaded others to
deal in the shares of building products supplier Aaronson Brothers after
learning of a planned takeover bid to be launched by Glunz AG, a German wood
company, the court heard.
Ms Staines's father bought 12,000 shares which were later sold for Pounds
3,000 profit. Mr Morrisey passed the information on to a contact who bought
5,000 shares. Mr Morrisey bought the shares back before the takeover was
announced and later sold them for a Pounds 1,500 profit.
Aaronson shares rose from 50p to 80p after the bid announcement in August
1990.
The pair gained the information about the bid from a friend, Mr Martin
Priddle, an accountant with KPMG Peat Marwick who was later sacked. He 'let
the cat out of the bag' two weeks before the announcement of the bid when he
met Mr Morrisey and Ms Staines at a garden party, prosecuting counsel said.
The prosecution was brought by the Department of Trade and Industry after an
investigation in November 1990.
</TEXT>
