<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Heseltine to review local authorities' powers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, yesterday announced
a 'far-reaching' review of local authorities' enforcement functions, after
complaints by business that many responsibilities were duplicated.
The move was welcomed by the Confederation of British Industry. But it could
clash with the review of local government structure in England being
conducted by Sir John Banham for the Department of the Environment.
Sir John's Local Government Commission has been asked by Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, to find ways to create all-purpose unitary
authorities to replace the two-tier system of district and county councils.
Mr Gummer has also recommended that the new authorities should not be very
large or remote. However, the DTI's review now appears to be re-examining
this advice.
Mr Heseltine's review will examine ways to minimise the costs to business
and the enforcers in such areas as building and planning control, trading
standards, environmental health, food safety and health and safety.
The DTI said: 'Concern has been expressed by business, including through the
Deregulation Task Forces, about the burdens placed upon them by the number
of different inspectors and enforcers who visit them in unco-ordinated ways
on similar subjects.'
The CBI said: 'We welcome this announcement delightedly. It echoes many of
the concerns we have expressed about duplication. We are concerned that
there should be consistency and not fragmentation of regulatory authorities.
'A lot will depend on what emerges from the Local Government Commission, but
fragmentation has been recommended in Wales.'
The Labour-led Association of County Councils said: 'This is going to
complicate matters for the local government review. We argued before the
Banham review started that the issue of enforcement functions should have
been sorted out first.'
In the Welsh local government reorganisation, trading standards officers are
trying to ensure that trading standards are covered by three large
authorities, although Wales will be split into 21 councils. Each council
would nominate members for the authority covering its area.
The DTI body will include officials from interested departments and
representatives of local authority associations. It must report within 90
days.
</TEXT>
