<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / New laws promised for media future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government made clear yesterday that it is determined to create a
legislative framework to cope with the 'multi-media future' - the merging of
industries such as computing, entertainment and telecommunications.
Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary, speaking two weeks after
announcing a review of cross-media ownership, said the government would be
negligent if it did not create a framework for such changes.
A vast new marketplace was developing and the government was determined to
ensure there were British stallholders. Mr Brooke said broadcasting was a
national resource of the greatest importance.
'I would be negligent in my duty if I looked at purely commercial arguments
at the expense of cultural. Equally, a short-sighted clinging to the status
quo and a failure to recognise the changing needs of the industry would be
self-defeating,' he said.
Newsprint and videotape were powerful weapons and could do great harm 'in
the wrong hands or concentrated too heavily in too few hands'.
Mr Brooke said the UK could look forward to the multi-media future with
confidence because of the strength of its programme-making, its advanced
digital and satellite technology and the 'vibrancy' of its national
newspaper market. The review of cross-media ownership is expected to take at
least six months.
