<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / World Trade News: Pact freezes Chinese textile exports to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER, SIMON HOLBERTON and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING, HONG KONG, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US and China struck a last-minute textile quota agreement yesterday that
effectively freezes Chinese imports to the US at present levels and averts a
serious trade dispute.
Under the agreement, signed in Beijing by special trade representatives,
China's exports to the US market will not be allowed to grow as they have in
the past three years. The move will cost Chinese exporters about Dollars
700m (Pounds 472.9m) and result in a 13 per cent reduction in expected
shipments to the US in 1994-1996.
China also agreed to penalties, proposed by the US, for violations of quota
restrictions.
A senior US trade official, briefing reporters, said the Chinese had agreed
reluctantly to the quota penalties, but had clearly recognised that the row
over illicit trans-shipments, overshipments and false labelling was harming
China's image and trade prospects.
Trans-shipment involves Chinese-manufactured goods being transported through
third countries - such as Malaysia, Hong Kong and the United Arab Emirates -
to disguise their origin.
US officials believe that the value of illegal trans-shipments of textile
items exceeds Dollars 2bn annually.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, yesterday welcomed the textile
pact as 'the beginning of a healthier and more productive relationship'
between the US and China.
Mr Henry Tang, textiles chief at the Hong Kong Federation of Industry, said
the three-year agreement was good news for the colony.
'Our position as the major trans-shipment port (for Chinese textiles) is
assured,' Mr Tang said.
The deal was seen as boding well for an agreement to extend China's most
favoured nation (MFN) status by the US administration this year. For Hong
Kong, the extension of MFN is far more important than the current dispute
about trans-shipment irregularities.
Sir Hamish Macleod, Hong Kong financial secretary, said yesterday that
renewal of China's MFN could not be taken for granted. He said that, if
China were to lose its MFN status in the US market, growth in Hong Kong
might be halved from its forecast level of 5 per cent this year.
China's textile exports to the US under the Multi-Fibre Arrangement amounted
to Dollars 4.68bn in 1993. Shipments of silk clothes - the fastest-growing
Chinese garment exports to the US - accounted for a further Dollars 2.5bn.
China's trade surplus with the US reached Dollars 25bn last year, prompting
demands by US Congress members for steps to restrain Chinese imports.
After the signing ceremony, Ms Jennifer Hillman, the chief US negotiator,
said the agreement would 'provide for consistent and orderly growth of
China's textile and textile product exports to the US'.
China dominates textile exports to the US, accounting for 20-25 per cent of
all clothing sold. US textile industry representatives say that illegal
Chinese imports have cost 50,000 US jobs. US customs seized some Dollars
581m of textiles illegally imported into the US since 1991, during the
previous agreement.
Mrs Wu Yi, China's trade minister, expressed satisfaction with the
agreement, appearing relieved that US demands had not been more severe.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CNZ  China, Asia.
