</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Bank chief eases fears of small companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, last night argued that
antagonism between banks and small companies was easing, and companies were
unlikely to be constrained from recovery by a lack of finance.
Mr George spoke after publishing a bank inquiry which found that tension had
been heightened by 'exaggerated expectations on one side, and insensitivity
on the other', but was caused mainly by the high rate of company failures.
The bank's largely optimistic conclusion was welcomed by groups representing
small businesses. The Confederation of British Industry said it would raise
the quality of debate on an issue of crucial importance to the economy.
High street banks also welcomed the results, including the finding that
banks were 'committed to the finance of the small firm sector', and that
companies recognised that banks were 'not public utilities' and had to make
profits.
The inquiry was conducted by Mr George last year after his appointment as
governor. It followed two studies by the Bank on terms set by the
government, which cleared banks of not passing on interest rate cuts.
Sir Nicholas Goodison, president of the British Bankers' Association,
welcomed the findings. He said earlier inquiries had been 'politically
motivated' and too narrow.
The Bank's report criticised banks for having shown 'a lack of
sophistication and sensitivity in their dealings with small businesses',
particularly in setting charges and taking securities against loans. But Mr
George emphasised in a speech to the Scottish CBI and Scottish Enterprise
last night that he was 'very encouraged' by the inquiry, and by 'the extent
and variety of initiatives' taken by banks, small companies and the
government.
He said that improving access to finance for Britain's 2.5m small companies
was best tackled in 'many small steps across a wide front'. The damage
inflicted on banks and small companies was rooted in the economic volatility
of the past five years, and stable low-inflationary growth would 'go a long
way to reducing the tensions'.
The inquiry concluded that banks should offer businesses a wider range of
finance than overdrafts. It also suggested that venture capitalists and
'business angels' should be encouraged.
Initiative welcomed, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
