<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: Blow to Turkey's borrowing plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's plans to tap the international bond market were dealt a blow last
week when Moody's and Standard &amp; Poor's, the two leading credit rating
agencies, downgraded the country's debt rating.
Moody's cut Turkey's foreign debt rating to Ba1 from Baa3, which reduces it
from investment to sub-investment grade. Because of the borrowing rules
affecting some US institutions, Turkey may find it more difficult to sell
its paper in the Yankee bond market, the US market for foreign issuers. It
could also impair Turkey's ability to raise debt finance in Europe and
Japan.
Meanwhile, Standard &amp; Poor's lowered Turkey's debt rating from BBB to BBB -
, which keeps it just within the limit of investment grade ratings.
According to treasury figures, Turkey's external debt, both public and
private, stood at Dollars 59bn at the end of September, against Dollars 51bn
at the start of 1993. However, with a spate of new issues before the year
end, bankers estimate the figure is closer to Dollars 62bn.
Over the past two years, Ankara has looked increasingly to foreign debt to
finance the current account and budget, at a time of high domestic interest
rates. Shifting its borrowing from syndicated loans to bonds, it has been
able to diversify its investor base and improve the maturity profile of its
debt. Like other low-rated borrowers, Turkey offers attractive high-yielding
paper.
However, Moody's decision reflects continuing concern over Turkey's large
current account deficit and deteriorating budget picture. Although Moody's
notes improvements on tax reform, and state asset sales, the agency
forecasts further spending pressures and expects political concerns to force
the government to go slow on further reform. The S&amp;P downgrade also
reflected 'a lack of progress in combatting the fiscal deficit in 1993 and
the absence of a credible programme to reduce the deficit in the medium
term'.
For 1994, the Turkish treasury has announced a more conservative borrowing
target, with plans to float around Dollars 1.3bn of bonds to cover its
external financing needs.
In 1993, Turkey tapped Japanese, German and UK bond markets for close to
Dollars 4bn. In addition, Dollars 3.8bn of project financing has been
extended to Turkish public sector enterprises and local municipalities.
Turkey issued a sterling bond for the first time in 1993 and this year is
looking at possible issues in both the French and Spanish bond markets.
The 1994 budget envisages Dollars 2bn in foreign debt interest repayments.
The current account deficit is expected to come back slightly to Dollars
4.4bn, according to Treasury estimates, compared with a provisional estimate
of Dollars 5bn in 1993.
</TEXT>
