<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Concerns of oversupply caused by last Friday's announcement that the finance
ministry would be selling government bonds outright for the first time in 11
years, are expected to continue this week.
The yield on the No 157 10-year benchmark, which closed up 11 basis points
at the week's high of 3.165 per cent on Friday, may rise further as
investors take profits on their positions.
The government, which usually sells bonds with repurchase agreements,
expects to sell about Y900bn to fund the forthcoming economic support
package. The MoF sold Y800bn worth of bonds without repurchase agreements in
1978, Y300bn in 1981, Y1,500bn in 1982 and Y900bn in 1983. The outright
sales via the Bank of Japan could start this week.
Meanwhile, hopes of a discount rate cut have receded due to the recent
strength on the stock market. The Nikkei index gained 4.7 per cent last week
on active buying by foreign investors, and analysts expect fund flows into
Tokyo could last if Asian stock markets continue to slide.
Investors are expected to focus on political developments this week. Prime
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa wants to push the political reform bill through
on Wednesday. A delay in the upper house could further postpone the economic
stimulus package, due to be announced Thursday.
</TEXT>
