<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prices of Treasury notes and bonds suffered a series of blows at the end of
last week as the market took fright at a second straight day of strong
economic news.
Thursday had already seen the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond shed almost a
point in response to stronger than expected growth in consumer spending.
Then on Friday, it lost nearly half a point more when the Federal Reserve
reported that industrial production had jumped by 0.7 per cent in December
compared with expectations of a figure nearer 0.4 per cent.
After that, the coming week should look relatively tame. For a start, the
market is closed today for Martin Luther King Memorial Day - and the rest of
the week is likely to mark a hiatus after last week's activity as investors
regroup in readiness for the release of the key data for January employment,
due out on February 4.
That said, the market will not be left without some data to chew over. The
figures for November's trade deficit are expected to show a slight shrinkage
from October's Dollars 10.5bn on Wednesday.
On Thursday, December housing starts should show a slight fall from
November's 1.43m and new filings for unemployment claims are expected to
have stood at 325,000 in the week ended January 15.
</TEXT>
