<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Company News This Week: Oil price weakens Elf's last figures
before privatisation - Other companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Elf-Aquitaine, the French state-owned oil group which is slated for
privatisation, will announce its provisional results for 1993 tomorrow.
Mr Philippe Jaffre, who took over as chairman last August, has already
warned that profits will see a sharp fall from FFr6.2bn (Pounds 710m) to
just over FFr1bn. The decline reflects the weak oil price, the write-down of
certain oil assets and Mr Jaffre's desire to clean up the group's balance
sheet ahead of Elf's privatisation, which is due to be launched later this
month.
Chrysler: The US car manufacturer is expected to report strong fourth
quarter figures tomorrow. The domestic car and light truck market is
enjoying solid growth, with sales up 8 per cent in 1993, and Chrysler has
been faring particularly well thanks to a strong line-up of new high-margin
vehicles.
Its December sales were up 7 per cent on 1992 and were its strongest for the
month in five years. Forecasts of fourth quarter earnings per share range
from Dollars 1.37 to Dollars 1.90, with a mean around Dollars 1.60.
Volvo: Shareholders will elect a new seven-man board on Wednesday, following
the clear-out that accompanied last month's collapse of the planned merger
with Renault.
Mr Bert-Olof Svanholm, chief executive of the Swedish operations of Asea
Brown Boveri, is expected to be confirmed as chairman, with Renault chief
executive Louis Schweitzer also gaining a seat. Nominations to all seven
posts have been made by shareholders accounting for at least 40 per cent of
Volvo's votes and are unlikely to be opposed.
Gestetner Holdings: The UK-based office and photographic equipment
distributor is expected to announce full-year pre-tax losses of up to Pounds
38m on Thursday after taking a Pounds 48.3m provision at the interim stage,
mainly to cover the restructuring of its European operations.
The results will be the last before Inchcape, the international services
group which bought 15.3 per cent of Gestetner in May, must decide whether to
exercise its option to acquire convertible unsecured loan stock, enabling it
to lift its stake to 24.6 per cent. The exercise price on the option, which
expires on July 1, is equal to 172p a share - well above the current 140p
level.
Photo-Me International: The world's largest photo-booth manufacturer and
operator is likely to show first-half pre-tax profits little changed from
last year's Pounds 10.5m, when it reports tomorrow.
</TEXT>
