<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Unions criticise job-saving deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sheffield City Council hopes to repeat last year's model job-saving deal
which involved a small cut in pay for its 15,000 employees in return for job
security and an extra seven days' holiday. But union officials warn that the
deal is unlikely to be accepted for a second year.
Compulsory redundancies were avoided last year as a result of the deal,
which cut pay by 3.25 per cent. This year, according to union officials, the
council wants a further cut of 2.75 per cent but is not offering extra
holiday.
The deal produced a saving of Pounds 7m for the council last year. This year
it needs another Pounds 9m saving in employee costs as part of a Pounds 31m
package of cuts.
There was strong support for last year's deal from Nupe, the public-service
union, and Nalgo - now part of Unison - and narrower support from the GMB
general union.
But Unison said yesterday: 'We were persuaded to accept a pay cut . . . on
the basis that it was going to resolve the budget problems and give the
council a year in which to restructure. It seems that we are right back in
that position again and it's all been for nothing.'
</TEXT>
