<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Education bill stalled by angry Tory peers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government may be unable to push its education bill through parliament
without substantial revisions because of growing opposition to the measures
in both the Commons and the Lords.
The bill, which would create a teacher-training agency and restrict the use
of student union funds for political activity, was introduced into the Lords
last month. But, according to backbench Conservative MPs, the legislation
came under such intense fire from peers that ministers are uneasy about
moving it to the committee stage where it would be scrutinised clause by
clause.
One Tory MP said the government was moving on to other legislation while it
decides what to do. He said: 'The government did not anticipate that it
would be so severely opposed and it has shaken them a bit.'
The bill was attacked at its second reading debate last month by a number of
Tory peers as an infringement of the rights of student unions. That was
followed by a second challenge from a Lords procedure committee which
complained that the bill had been poorly drafted.
The Lords committee on the scrutiny of delegated powers said that the bill
gave the education secretary almost unlimited powers to decide how student
unions could spend their money. 'The House may regard as inappropriate the
delegation of legislative power to interfere with the freedom of association
of students,' the committee said.
Lord Graham, a Labour whip in the Lords, said no date had been set for the
bill to go its committee stage up to the week beginning February 7. 'A bill
that received its second reading on December 7 should have moved on by now,'
he said. 'The government is clearly concerned by what is going on.'
Department of Education officials believe that the bill is not facing any
real difficulties. 'We are determined to press on,' said one.
But if the bill moves to the Commons in its present form, it would probably
be opposed by two former education ministers, Mr Robert Jackson and Sir
Rhodes Boyson, and by the Conservative chairman of the Commons education
committee, Sir Malcolm Thornton.
Mr Jackson said last week that the proposals to restrict the rights of
student unions were so unjust that they they might infringe the European
Convention on Human Rights.
Sir Rhodes believes that the reform of student union funding was
satisfactorily dealt with by legislation he introduced when he was an
education minister 10 years ago. 'We should really be focusing on more
important issues now,' he said.
</TEXT>
