<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Whistleblowers spotlight fraud at work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Corruption and financial malpractice in the workplace were the most common
concerns of workers who contacted a charity set up to give legal advice to
employees.
The first report of Public Concern at Work, the charity that advises
so-called 'whistleblowers' - people who expose malpractice in the workplace
 -is published today. It says that a third of the calls the charity dealt
with in its first month of operation concerned corruption and potential
fraud.
It also found that the National Health Service was the largest single source
of complaints.
In one case support staff at a trust hospital - not named in the report
because of the charity's duty of confidentiality - raised worries about a
doctor who they said intimidated nursing staff and colleagues. They also
alleged that his patients had a significantly higher mortality rate than
those of his colleagues.
The charity advised a union official to raise the problem informally with
the hospital's chief executive. The result was that the working atmosphere
improved and the doctor's medical performance was being monitored.
Mr Guy Dehn, director of the charity, said the hierarchical nature of the
NHS meant 'the idea that nurses, blue-collar or clerical staff could even
politely suggest that the surgeon is chopping off the wrong leg is unheard
of'.
Of some 200 calls received by the charity in the first month, a quarter
involved people with serious workplace concerns. Others wanted information
on the legal service or had private grievances not covered under the
charity's remit, which insists on a public-interest element in the concern.
The report said 25 out of 51 people who had blown the whistle on their
employers before contacting the charity had been victimised for speaking
out, and 17 had been either sacked or forced to resign.
It added that people at all levels, including directors, senior managers and
consultants, had sought advice. Concerns included unsafe buses, mail-order
fraud, suspected tendering fraud in local authorities, abuse of children in
care, dubious methods in financial services and drugs misuse at work.
The charity said that its advice in one case prevented the award of a Pounds
750,000 freight contract to a company which had been running unsafe
vehicles. The safety inspector for the customer company ignoring his worries
about the vehicles' roadworthiness and suspected he was receiving bribes
from the contractor.
The inspector was advised to raise his fears discreetly with the company
finance director. This led to the contract being awarded elsewhere, but the
suspect manager was still in post and the inspector was considering leaving
his job.
Public Concern at Work, Lincoln's Inn House, 42 Kingsway, London WC2B 6EN.
Pounds 2.50.
</TEXT>
<XX>
