<TEXT>
The contracting-out of National Health Service cleaning work to private
companies is covered by the European Union's transfer regulations, which
protect the pay and conditions of workers for at least one year, according
to a Liverpool industrial tribunal.
Following an Employment Appeals Tribunal ruling last year it had been
assumed that the Transfer of Undertakings - Protection of Employment (Tupe)
regulations - which often make public sector contracts less attractive to
the private sector, would not generally apply to NHS cleaning.
In September Mr Justice Wood upheld an industrial tribunal judgment that
Tupe did not apply when 107 cleaners at Orsett Hospital in Basildon were
transferred from Initial Health Care Services to the Pall Mall Services
Group.
But the latest judgment has ruled that the contracting out of cleaning at
Walton Hospital to Taylorplan Services in October 1992 is covered by Tupe.
However, the two decisions are not necessarily in conflict as the Orsett
case involved a transfer between two private groups.
The significance of the decision is that it has established that an in-house
cleaning operation, which had won the original tender to clean the hospital
from 1986 to 1992, can be regarded as a separate 'undertaking', at least in
an NHS trust, and a transfer can be deemed to have occurred in spite of the
minimal transfer of equipment and premises.
Unison, the public-service union, welcomed the decision on behalf of the 120
cleaners who will qualify for some compensation for the lower pay and
sickness benefit they have received from Taylorplan. Some of the 25 people
who were not taken on by Taylorplan may also be able to claim unfair
dismissal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
