<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Accountancy firms voice optimism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountancy firms in London are beginning to express cautious optimism about
economic recovery and its impact on their business.
Mr Michael Fowle, senior partner for London and the south-east for KPMG Peat
Marwick, said: 'I think things are beginning to turn up, although we are
lagging comment in the papers.'
Mr Michael Boyd, head of the London office of Ernst &amp; Young, said: 'Overall
it's going to be another tough year, but we will hold our own.'
Most firms have reported almost static fee income in their most recent
results, compared with substantial growth in the late 1980s.
Consulting suffered particularly heavily, while audit and tax work have been
stable against a backdrop of growing competition between the firms.
In the last few months the compensating fillip provided by income from
insolvency work has begun to decline, reflecting the drop in the number of
company failures.
Both KPMG and Ernst &amp; Young said corporate finance and investigations work
were beginning to pick up, in line with the recovery in corporate
transactions and rise in the equity markets.
