<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JAN 94 / Greece abandons pledge on staffing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's Socialist government has unveiled legislation which is likely to
create 30,000 permanent civil service posts, writes Kerin Hope in Athens.
The draft law, to be presented to parliament later this month, appears to
signal the Socialists' abandonment of an earlier commitment to the European
Union to cut public sector staffing levels.
Permanent jobs for public sector workers employed on contract for at least
six years would swell the civil service by about 8 per cent and further
burden this year's budget.
The Socialist government assured the European Commission earlier this month
that Greece would renew efforts to cut its borrowing requirement, estimated
at 13.9 per cent of gross domestic product in 1993.
The former conservative government's pledge to cut thousands of public
sector jobs under a structural reform programme agreed with the EU was
dropped last summer.
The public sector wage bill soared after the conservatives granted extra pay
rises and made more than 20,000 patronage appointments.
</TEXT>
