<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / Sharp increase in US production boosts shares to record
levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US industrial production grew at an annual rate of 7.5 per cent in real
terms in the fourth quarter of last year, a further sign of the accelerating
pace of economic recovery, figures from the Federal Reserve indicated
yesterday.
The news prompted a strong rise in share prices and the Dow Jones Industrial
Average finished the day 24.77 up at a new high of 3,867.2. Bond prices fell
on fears that faster growth would bring forward the timing of an interest
rate rise.
As the Clinton administration puts the final touches to this year's budget,
due early next month, senior officials are increasingly confident about the
economic outlook.
In an address in New York yesterday, Mr Robert Rubin, chairman of the White
House National Economic Council, forecast a robust, sustained recovery.
He said there was 'very little probability of inflation reigniting' and
predicted 3 per cent growth this year. Mr Rubin said economic conditions
would also be favourable in 1995 and 1996 because, by then, the US would be
boosted by economic recovery in Japan and Europe.
In an apparent preview of the budget, Mr Rubin also predicted the US would
make more rapid progress than expected in reducing the federal budget
deficit.
The deficit would fall to 'substantially under 2 per cent of GDP' over five
years, he said. Last year's budget projected a deficit of 3.1 per cent in
1998.
The Fed report showed production up 0.7 per cent in December after strong
gains in preceding months.
Although led by a surge in car production, output strength appears broadly
based, with nearly every industrial sector registering healthy gains.
Excluding cars, production was up 0.5 per cent last month, the same rise as
in November.
The rate of industrial capacity utilisation rose to 83.5 per cent, above its
long-term average of 81.9 per cent but still below the 84.8 per cent
registered at the peak of the 1980s boom.
The University of Michigan's consumer sentiment index was reported to have
risen sharply in early January to 95.8 against 88.2 in December.
Currencies, Page 11
US stocks, Page 19
Markets, Weekend II
</TEXT>
